{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506681"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:45:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:45:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2557"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2557"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.19,0.09,0.54,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2557"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48169"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2557"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2557"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33089"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"3749"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2624"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2649"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39192"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44274"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48169"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA nine-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his father with a one-day history of fever, abdominal pain, vomiting and myalgia. He is originally from Nigeria. His father reports that some children at his son\u0027s school have also been sick this week with rash and fevers, however, his son has not had a rash. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is up to date with immunisations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears very unwell with a pulse rate of 120/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Urgent blood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 55 g/L (115-155)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 4.0 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 140 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReticulocytes \u0026lt;1% (0.5-2.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevious blood tests show a haemoglobin baseline of 85 g/L.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely precipitant for this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Streptococcus pneumoniae","Coxsackie virus A16","Hepatitis A","Parvovirus B19","Measles"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child is experiencing typical symptoms of an acute infective illness. The history of chronic anaemia and his ethnicity strongly suggests sickle cell disease (SCD), which is endemic in sub-Saharan Africa. Patients with SCD may develop aplastic crisis, most commonly precipitated by \u003Cstrong\u003Eparvovirus B19\u003C/strong\u003E infection. This is characterised by an acute drop in haemoglobin with reticulocytopenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with SCD are at risk of infections due to encapsulated pathogens including \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, Haemophilus influenzae, \u003C/em\u003Edue to the associated hyposplenia/functional asplenia. However, they typically cause pneumonia, meningitis, or bacteraemia rather than aplastic crisis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoxsackie virus A16\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of hand, foot, and mouth disease in children. While it can cause fever and general malaise, it does not typically cause aplastic crisis in sickle cell patients and would usually present with characteristic lesions on the hands, feet, and mouth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis A\u003C/strong\u003E virus infection can cause fever and abdominal pain, but it primarily affects the liver and would not cause an aplastic crisis. Additionally, jaundice would be a more prominent feature if this were the cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasles\u003C/strong\u003E virus can cause severe illness in children, but it typically presents with a characteristic rash, cough, and conjunctivitis (the \u00223 Cs\u0022). It does not typically cause aplastic crisis in sickle cell disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sickle cell disease is common in sub-Saharan Africa","Parvovirus B19 is the most common cause of aplastic crisis in patients with sickle cell disease.","Aplastic crisis in sickle cell disease is characterized by a sudden drop in haemoglobin with reticulocytopenia."],"references":["Ware RE, de Montalembert M, Tshilolo L, Abboud MR. Sickle cell disease. Lancet. 2017;390(10091):311-23. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28159390/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33089"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2557"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33089"},